segments.text: As I was saying that Guy Warren, the president of Chamber of Commerce, had the good sense to appoint Mr. Lon C. Hill, who was president of the power company, Central Power and Light Company.
And his company took the position that Corpus Christi is the prime city of their system.

and was destined to go places and expand and be a big city and be a big market for their power, they gave him an unlimited expense account that he could use in connection with working with the Area Development Committee.
And he used it very effectively.
He would have luncheons for these various committees
particularly the subcommittee, the working committee.
He would get them together and tell them this is what we want to do and how to do it.
And he did it in a very good-natured way, but very firm.
I recall one time he took us in the CPNL boardroom.
We had a serious problem to settle between the city and the county and the navigation district.
And he says, I want you three fellas or you three agencies to get in this room and start talking.
And as he went out, he says, now, I'm going to lock the door.
And when you come to an answer, I'll unlock the door and let you in or let you out.
Well, it was good natured he wouldn't do it.
But after we got through, he took us out to dinner, and we solved the problem.
But that's the kind of an atmosphere we had to work with.
And it was very effective.

Well, when this report was published, the Area Development Committee, the Comprehensive Plan, it was called, for Corpus Christi area, the Area Development Committee, at their expense, had a big banquet.
They filled the biggest hotel room that they had and invited all of the citizens committees and all the leaders, the Area Development Committee,
and their wives.
And it was the Driscoll Hotel at that time.
And they had a very large ballroom.
We never had one as big as that since.
But they filled it.
And the purpose was to present the community with the plan.
So after the dinner, they got up.
And they had Bartholomew explain the plan briefly.
And then they called on each of the political leaders and said, now, you've been a part of this plan.
You worked along with it.
And it's going to be you that's going to carry it out, not the Area Development Committee.
We're citizens.
We've been willing to put up most of the money.
The city and the county and the navigation district each put up $10,000.
But otherwise, it was all citizens' money.
So they called on each one of them to talk.
Each one of them got up and said, now, we'll do our part.
They even had a representative of the city
the federal government there, congressmen, and the state representative.
And I remember very well when they came around to the city, the mayor had been a member of this committee.
I knew what was coming.
So prior to this meeting, he had gotten past
the largest bond issue that the city had ever passed.
And it was all based on this plan.
And he said, if it isn't in the plan, I don't want it in the bond issue.
So when he got up and he said, well, here's our contribution.
We've got so many million dollars already voted to carry out our part of the plan.
And the other political leaders said the same thing.
Now, this is quite a long ways to come from the time that we had this commission form of government.
And there was political backbiting.
And nobody wanted to do anything.
And nobody would vote bonds.
So based on the plan, they got the bond issue passed.
And they went right to work on it.
We built a dam right away, new water supply.
We got busy on the bridge.
It took a little while longer to get the airport problem worked out because it was a conflict with the military airspace.
And we had to wait till that got cleared up.
The State Highway Department
went to work on a plan for a freeway system.
And local citizens agreed to do their share in buying the right of way, in addition to what they had in this.
The plan did have parallel streets, but these were modified.
the State Highway Department offered the freeways.
But it was all fit in with the plan.
From time to time, there were minor modifications.
But basically, the plan went on up.
They did everything in the plan.
And once we got started on implementing this plan, the citizens were impatient.
They wanted it.
They didn't want it on the 15 or 20 year schedule that we had.
They wanted it faster than that.
So we condensed it and still were able to finance it.
And I had something else on that.
On the freeways?
Yeah, well, we implemented all parts of the plan very much as they were proposed.
One example, in the school plan, the schools were generally located by using the system of circles.
And the school administration were so anxious to have the schools located in the right place that they went out and bought the land that was at the center of the circle.
And in a few instances, they were so conscientious about trying to put it in the right place that they bought land that was maybe not as suitable as maybe a block away would have been.
It wasn't properly drained or something.
But this was an attitude of their conscientiousness to do it according to the plan.
As faithfully as possible.
As faithfully as possible.
And they did.
And the one thing that was not implemented was urban renewal.
This city was free enterprise.
And there was a group, including some of the members of the Area Development Committee, that felt that this was socialistic and that they wouldn't subscribe to it.
And they got a law passed in the legislature requiring a referendum for urban renewal to be undertaken.
They had a referendum.
And it failed four to one.
So the only thing that was not implemented in the plan was the urban renewal.
It was tried again two other times, and it failed each time.
So this city was not oriented to urban renewal.
I think it's appropriate to go back now and talk a little bit about our harbor and ship channel.
As you know, the Gulf Coast here is subject to hurricanes.
In 1919, we had a very serious hurricane here that virtually wiped off the development on an area north of the bridge called North Beach.
A great many lives were lost.
the city decided that they needed some protection.
At the same time we were talking about building a harbor here, we had a ship channel that was a shallow channel that served the piers out in front of the town.
But these were shallow draft vessels and were not adequate.
The citizens here went to Congress and got this city designated for a deep harbor, a deep draft harbor.
Congress passed it and then voted the funds to dig a deeper channel and to dig a deep harbor.
This was completed in 1926.
at which time the Bascule Bridge was built.
The harbor was much smaller than it is today.
But in order to get this harbor, the community and the state had to provide a seawall protection in front of the city.
The local citizens went to the legislature
and got an act passed that was called tax remission.
And it was for seven counties around here that all the state taxes would be remitted to a fund called the Seawall Protection Fund for Corpus Christi.
At that time, the development around here was some farmland.
But a lot of it was brush, and it was just coming into farmland, good productive farmland.
And the taxes weren't very high.
So this act didn't yield an awful lot of money.
But it did yield enough that we could put a breakwater out in front of the city.
And that is the breakwater that's out there now, those rocks.
This satisfied the federal government of protection of the harbor.
But as long about this time, I mentioned that we had discovered oil in this area and that the farmland is expanding rapidly.
And we were producing a great deal of cotton, which was being shipped out of the new harbor
And the taxes for this seven-county area increased substantially.
So it was quite a bit of funds there available.
The community then decided that they wanted a seawall in front of the city, and that Gutzon Borglum was a resident of Beeville.
He made a plaster model for the seawall here and even offered to build a statue of Christ and give it to the city if they'd follow his model.
For some reason, they didn't go along with that.
But later on, they sent committees all over the United States looking at seawalls.
They came back and decided what kind of a seawall they wanted.
And they engaged a firm of engineers, and they went ahead and designed a seawall.
And what they did with this seawall was to place it out into the bay, about a block or two blocks out into the bay.
And then they filled the land behind the seawall
with dredged material and created land.
Some of this land went to the owners of the adjacent property for riparian rights, but about one block of it was left for public use.
And this is what made the beautiful bayfront.
The seawall was built and completed in 1941.
just before World War II.
Who did the work on it?
Who did all the construction?
Well, there was a local construction firm.
It might have been Brown and Root.
I'm not sure.
Anyhow, the Meyers and Noyes were the engineers.
It wasn't done then with the WPA labor?
No.
No, it was all contract.
Because there's a rumor that that was done with WPA.
No, there was no WPA.
It was all done with bond money.
No, all done with money from this fund.
The special fund.
They issued bonds on it, but they paid off these bonds from the revenue from this tax remission.
And that was...
finally paid off in about 1950, and the remission act was then repealed.
We probably should mention that Goodson Borglum then went on to be the sculptor at Mount Rushmore.
Yeah, yeah.
I understand that the statue of Christ that was destined for, was offered to Corpus Christi
went to Spearfish, South Dakota.
South Dakota.
Of course, Goodson Borglum all the time was working on Mount Rushmore.
During that same period.
During the same period.
Now, after the war, this land between the, out in front of the, between the sea wall
old shoreline that was owned by the public was undeveloped.
It had a lot of shell and sand and wasn't very attractive and had no planning.
So the city then, with the encouragement of the Chamber of Commerce, employed the landscape firm and city planning firm
of Hare and Hare out of Kansas City to design the seawall, the landscaping on the seawall and the piers that were part of the seawall, the T-heads we call them.
So the landscaping that is there is the result of the design that was made by the very famous landscape architectural firm of Hare and Hare.
Since going back to the ship channel, the ship channel was extended several times.
In about 1955, it was extended several miles.
In connection with the Bascule Bridge Removal Project, the head of navigation in the ship channel, or the harbor, was extended about four miles up the channel.
And the railroad bridge was built up at the upper part of the channel.
As part of the land use plan, it was conceived that the industry all ought to be on the north side of the city near the ship channel.
Two reasons.
One, the prevailing wind was from the southeast, and it blew the industrial odors
away from the city if it was over there.
Also that we wanted the Bayfront to be kept clean and most of it in public ownership for use of recreation and the beauty of the Bayfront.
This is all part of the land use plan
that was included in the area development plan.
And the city has adhered to it remarkably well.
One of the problems that Corpus Christi had was drainage.
Fortunately, most of the city is 14 feet or above
except for the downtown area and on Corpus Christi Beach.
But strangely enough, the slope of the land above was away from the bay so that in order to drain the land on which the city was to be built, it was necessary to dig channels that
would go through the bluff and into the bay.
Four or five large channels were built, Louisiana, Carmel Parkway, and a couple of others.
Now these were wide and originally were open ditches, but as the city
developed, the ditches were not acceptable.
And large boxes, concrete boxes, were placed in these ditches to carry off the water.
And all the feeder drainage was funneled into these big channels and big boxes and shunted into the bay.
In some cases, they were several hundred feet wide.
They were covered and landscaped and made recreation areas.
So as a result, you'll find several areas in the city that have wide open spaces running towards the bay.
It gives an openness to the area.
developed part of the city.
Has that system worked well?
It has worked perfectly.
How about during hurricanes?
We have no problems during hurricanes.
We're above the high point.
The only problem that we've had was in the downtown area.
After the seawall was built, the seawall was higher than the main business district.
So as part of the seawall construction, a large drainage box sewer, storm sewer, was placed in Water Street.
And all of the water that falls in this area goes into this big drainage box.
And at either end, one on the north end and one on the south end,
There are large pumps, a series of large pumps, that will pump this water out even though the water in the bay is higher than the land in the downtown district.
The pumps are strong enough to pump against the hydraulic head of the bay.
And we've never had any serious problem.
One time, one of the pumps got stuck and wouldn't pump water out.
And enough rainfall came in that the water got up to the door sills.
The council was very much perturbed and made sure that the pumps were in good working order.
They start those pumps and run them every few days to make sure that they have proper operating for them all year round.
Well, you take that railroad line that goes out of San Antonio, goes to Del Rio.
Now, every so often along there, they had a little town where they had a water plant.
They had a water tank.
When they got to Uvalde, they laid it out, 300-foot square blocks centered around the railroad station, laid out by the railroad engineers.
But it was the city.
You take DeHannis.
And a whole bunch of those little cities all along there, they were all laid out the same way.
And they're there now.
Well, this is analogous to the Illinois experience of the Illinois Central Railroad, laying out all the towns.
Sure.
Sure they did.
Well, we got that.
Now, we got that up in West Texas, too.
A lot of those cities out there were laid out by the railroads.
But those were engineers, not planners.
Yeah, but they didn't have planners then.
No.
They were the planners.
Whatever it is, they were responsible for shaping our city, our towns.
Well, then, after that initial era was over, then a lot of planning was done for the small cities of Texas with consultants and
Well, the 701s, you mean.
Later the 701s.
But nothing was done before the 701s?
Very little.
Hare and Hare did something in Wichita Falls.
Yes.
There was something done in Austin.
Well, George Kresser did a lot of work up there in Fort Worth, some in Dallas, laying out the parkway system.
I don't know what he did in El Paso.
I'm not familiar with that.
He did a general plan in 1925.
Well, Bartholomew did something there, too, one time.
Another element in the development of our cities
speculative developers.
There were a whole lot of them.
They would, over here at Rockport and that area, they laid out miles and miles of area with streets.
What they would do, they would lay out the town with lots in the town, and then they'd bring people down here by train.
snowbirds.
They would put them in the train and then run them by and show them it.
And they actually brought in fruit trees and tied on grapefruit.
And so that when they went by, they said, see, look at the grapefruit.
But it was tremendous promotion like that.
And what they would do
And it created a great many problems.
And I know because I've done some work up in Rockport.
They would sell a lot in town to one of these people they'd bring down here on the train.
And then they'd give them, I think it was a five-acre tract out on the edge of town in the brush.
So they sold these things all over the world.
And so when you want to develop any area around there, you've got all the title problems of these people that own these little five-acre tracts.
And they're out of town.
It sounds like the Florida boom did it.
You can't assemble a tract of land large enough to really do any good with.
Summing up.
The first comprehensive plan, it is rather remarkable that a city that had been mainly a tourist center or a resort center was just coming into an industrial city
building of the ship channel and the discovery of oil, that the leaders of the community could get together and establish a city manager form of government, and in so doing, provided
the necessary charter provisions for the establishment of an official planning commission.
And in addition to that, the leaders, the economic leaders, the political leaders, and a great many of the citizens were able to come together
and unite in preparing a comprehensive plan for the city.
The plan was technically very well done, but in addition, the plan provided for the means of financing it
And...
